@node "WhatIs" "What Is ..."
@next "Req"
@prev "Main"


Update Index will make a wonderful thing! :)

You probably got Your INDEX list 6 months ago, and are updating it all the
time with new files, etc, etc. Do You EVER look at 4. column!? Age!?

Age is in fact the 'number of weeks the file is on AmiNet'. So, if You want
to know HOW old the file You want to get is, just take a look at 'Age'
column.

However, 6 months = 27 weeks. Slowly, Your list is out-of-date.

Here comes UI! :)))

UI is still in kind of beta 'development' (what's there in it to develop!?).
UI will take a INDEX list, and once a week raise the "Age" column for +1.


@{"NEXT" link "Req" 0}
@endnode

@node "Req" "Requirements"
@next "Usage"
@prev "WhatIs"


Requirements:

- An Amiga
- OS 3.X
- AmiNet INDEX file
- s:Startup-Sequence ;)

UI was tested on A4000/040 & OS3.1. Haven't tested it on 2.X, and have no
idea if it works, but I presume it will work on A500 also ;)


@{"NEXT" link "Usage" 0}
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"
@next "Author"
@prev "Req"


Copy UI to some nice directory.

After that, there are 3 ways for starting it:

1) Place it in s:Startup-sequence, at the beggining (before SysPic i.e., so
You have some nice pictures to watch while UI works :). Looks like...


dh0:c/CheckValidating dh0:
dh0:c/CheckValidating dh1:
dh0:c/CheckValidating dh2:

C:SetPatch QUIET

c:SysPic sys:fortutil/SysPic/Pic*.iff 1 21 bf so vc bb

dh2:sc/UI/UI dh1:temp/index Sun
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

UI has 2 parameters.

UI <index file> <the day of the week You want to update it>

The day of the week MUST have 3 letters, like on Amiga. That means:

Mon - Monday
Tue - Tuesday
Wed - Wednesday
Thu - Thursday
Fri - Friday
Sat - Saturday
Sun - Sunday

So, if You want to update Your INDEX every monday, You will enter something
like...

--------------------- s: startup-sequence -----------------------------

...

c:setpatch quiet

c:UI dh1:AmiNet/Index Mon

...

-------------------------   CUT HERE :)   -----------------------------

When You reset Your Amiga, UI will take a look which day it is. If it finds
out "MONDAY" :), updating begins. When booting, Amiga will do DisplayBeep()
(it's Flash() in fact :), to let You know it started working. After it
finishes, it will "Beep" again. UI will create a small 'control' file in S:
directory, which helps him to see if updating was executed. Please don't
delete it. It's called s:UI.ack. When next day comes, UI will delete it by
itself, don't worry :)

2) Start it manually. Simply, on prompt, enter:

7.System> c:UI dh1:temp/index Mon

and UI will update index. The same thing with S:UI.ack will happen, and it
will not allow You to update INDEX file until (at least) next day! Except if
You don't delete S:UI.ack! :)

3) If You use schedulers, You can easily make it start at exact time, and
when it finishes, PLEASE, delete s:UI.ack by hand, because UI will not be
started until next week. So, file will stay in S:, and next week, it will
understand that he already updated INDEX that day.





At this moment, UI will NOT replace Your old INDEX file, but will rather
make a updated copy of it, called <index>.tmp (where <index> is the name of
Your INDEX file). I didn't find any nasty bugs, but...

UI makes the backup in the same dir where INDEX is located.

There is no output, so everything may look boring. But be patient, it will
finish updating sooner or later! :)))

If anybody require version that replaces original INDEX or something else,
please write me just one mail! :)


